AR2786(The most left one and the biggest) ‚û°Ô∏è AR2785 ‚û°Ô∏è AR2783(on the right a small faint black area)

No solar filter No problem we go old school projection method

The projection method was first used by famous muslim scientist Ibn al-Haytham to view the solar eclipse. He is the first person to view the eclipse without any harm.

The picture isn't perfect as I tried this method for the first time I just set my phone with timed burst on Auto Mode and project the image on a canvas.

Messier 45 (Plaides)

This is one of the open cluster that you can easily see with naked eyes and in almost any sky until there is no cloud. It is also called seven sisters because of the seven brighter stars present in the cluster.

I didn't capture much detail as was eager to capture orion, running man, flame and horsehead nebula üôÇ

Shot on Canon 700D with 75-300mm kit lens at 200mm

Lights 200 x2.5" ISO1600
Darks 30 x2.5" ISO1600

Stacked in Sequator
Post Processed in Adobe Photoshop CC

Zodiacal light (Subah-e-Kaazib)  also called false Dawn

Zodiacal light is a faint, diffuse, and roughly triangular white glow visible in the night sky that appears to extend from the vicinity of the Sun along the ecliptic or zodiac. Sunlight scattered by interplanetary dust in the zodiacal cloud causes this phenomenon.

I got lucky with the shot as Venus is mimicking like the SUN when it is at the dawn

10shots stacked in Sequator to increase dynamic range

10x30" ISO1600

The picture that sums up my entire trip to Caves City, Baluchistan, a bortle 2-3 Sky Region. I have never ever went to such a remote place and also never seen such dark skies that I couldn't able to see more than a feet.

The picture contains Flame Nebula Running Man Nebula and Orion Nebula and also there are very light pixels of horsehead can be seen but due to compression it can not be seen.

Lights 826x2.5" ISO1600
Darks 30x2.5" ISO1600

No Flats and Bias Frames

Total Exposure Time: 34.5mins
